<item>
            <title>[CASSANDRA-19454] Revert switch to approximate time in Dispatcher to avoid mixing with nanoTime() in downstream timeout calculations</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-19454</link>
                <project id="12310865" key="CASSANDRA">Apache Cassandra</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-15241&quot; title=&quot;Virtual table to expose current running queries&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;CASSANDRA-15241&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;CASSANDRA-15241&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; changed &lt;tt&gt;Dispatcher&lt;/tt&gt; to use the &lt;tt&gt;approxTime&lt;/tt&gt; implementation of &lt;tt&gt;MonotonicClock&lt;/tt&gt; rather than &lt;tt&gt;nanoTime()&lt;/tt&gt;, but clock drift between the two, can potentially cause queries to time out more quickly. We should be able to revert the &lt;tt&gt;Dispatcher&lt;/tt&gt; to use &lt;tt&gt;nanoTime()&lt;/tt&gt; again and similarly change &lt;tt&gt;QueriesTable} to {{nanoTime()&lt;/tt&gt; as well for consistency.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
